    "created_at": "2013-08-02T16:21:49Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-08-02T16:22:32Z",
    "body": "I think I prefer not to do this, for a few reasons:\n- If it exists at all, I'd like it to be called `enable-icu` since `enable-unicode` suggests (incorrectly) that the developer doesn't get unicode functionality at all without it. All text in Rust is unicode.\n- There are no non-ICU libraries that can fill the place here. At least none liberally licensed. All other full unicode implementations are either LGPL or proprietary (that I can find)\n- Our theory is that libextra is, eventually, going to consist of a curated selection of packages from the broader rustpkg ecosystem. Consequently it may well be necessary to enable building with or without nearly _every_ component we include a reference to, since users may not wish to bundle-together things they are not using. So I think special-casing the libicu bindings is a bit premature.\n\nLeaving this open to solicit further discussion: if you have strong opinions on this, let me know here.\n",
