    "body": "@graydon Well, I almost agree with you, but I put my first thought below.\n\n`--enable-icu` vs `--enable-unicode`: you are absolutely right since there is only the ICU binding for now.\n\nLicensing: I thought backends using platforms' API might useful for anyone who wants to reduce external dependencies. A backend using `std::unicode` might also be useful until `extra::unicode` provides a superset of `std::unicode` features. For now, `extra::unicode::*` is a _subset_ of std one AFAIK. (also useful for bootstraping when any code depends on `extra::unicode`?)\n\nlibextra and rustpkg ecosystem: I'm so excited and happy with your direction. However, I thought maintaining stable public APIs and ABIs with separated backends will be able to provide Unicode-aware libraries without forcing users to bundle ICU into their programs.\n\nPerhaps my understanding is different from the goal of `extra::unicode`.\n",
